== History == It is said that the origin dates back to when [[:en:Toda Ujikane|Toda Shitetsu]], while serving as the lord of the [[:en:Amagasaki Domain|Amagasaki Domain]] in [[:en:Settsu Province|Settsu Province]], enshrined a branch shrine from the Kifune Shrine of {{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto|qq=}}. Since Toda Shitetsu held lordship from {{ill|Genna Era|ja|Genna|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genna Era|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} 2 ([[:en:1616|1616]]) to [[:en:Kan'ei|Kan'ei Era]] 12 ([[:en:1635|1635]]), it is presumed that the branch was established during that period.
In [[:en:Kan'ei|Kan'ei Era]] 12 (1635), when the shrine was transferred to the [[:en:Ōgaki Domain|Ogaki Domain]] of [[:en:Mino Province|Mino Province]], it was relocated within [[:en:Ōgaki Castle|Ogaki Castle]]. In addition to this shrine, the {{ill|Toda clan|ja|戸田氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda clan|qq=}} enshrined seven shrines—including {{ill|Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano Shrine|ja|熊野権現|lt=Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano Shrine|lt_ja=熊野神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Shrine|qq=}}—inside Ogaki Castle.
Around April of [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] 4 ([[:en:1871|1871]]), the residents of Honmachi beneath Ogaki Castle petitioned the former lord, [[:en:Toda Ujitaka|Toda Shitetsu]], to enshrine the Kifune Shrine and Kumano Shrine as the guardian shrines of Honmachi. In October of the same year, at the site of the former Higashisōmon Yagura on the grounds of Shana‑in (a temple said to have been founded during the {{ill|Hakuhō|ja|白鳳|zh|白鳳|ru|Хакухо|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakuhō|qq=}} period by the Baekje prince monk Geumju—and abolished in [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] 2—located in the vicinity of Shimizu-cho, Ogaki City), the two shrines were merged and enshrined under the name Kifune Shrine.
== Transportation == * A 10‑minute walk from [[:en:Ōgaki Station|Ogaki Station]] on the {{ill|Tōkaidō Main Line|ja|Tōkaidō Main Line|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōkaidō Main Line|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, {{ill|Yoro Railway|ja|養老鉄道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoro Railway|qq=}}, and {{ill|Tarumi Railway|ja|樽見鉄道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tarumi Railway|qq=}}.
== Others == * Along the Minamonogawa, the Minamonogawa Promenade “Shiki no Michi” has been developed. The adjacent Kifune Plaza serves as a venue for various {{ill|Events|ja|イベント|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Events|qq=}} and is adorned with {{ill|Illumination|ja|イルミネーション|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Illumination|qq=}}. * During the annual “Honmachi Fire Burning Festival” held every November 3, Honmachi Street becomes a {{ill|Pedestrian Paradise|ja|歩行者天国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Pedestrian Paradise|qq=}}, hosting events such as a {{ill|Flea Market|ja|フリーマーケット|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Flea Market|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 蚤の市}}.
{{Shinto stub}}
